04435nam a22006615i 9780674272682DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20022002mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742726827 a10.4159/97806742726822doi  a(DE-B1597)613968  a(OCoLC)1294424590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a364.36/0944/09042211 aFishman, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Battle for Children :bWorld War II, Youth Crime, and Juvenile Justice in Twentieth-Century France /cSarah Fishman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Historical Studies ;v14200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 From Child Criminals to Juvenile Delinquents, 1810–1939 -- t2 The Experience of World War II for Children and Adolescents -- t3 The Wartime Juvenile Crime Wave as Manifested in the Courts -- t4 The Juvenile Delinquency Establishment during the War -- t5 Progressive Change in an Authoritarian Regime: Vichy’s Reforms -- t6 The Victory of Juvenile Justice Reform, 1945 to the Present -- tAppendix: Informational Sheet -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Battle for Children links two major areas of historical inquiry: crime and delinquency with war and social change. In a study based on impressive archival research, Sarah Fishman reveals the impact of the Vichy regime on one of history’s most silent groups—children—and offers enlightening new information about the Vichy administration. Fishman examines how French children experienced the events of war and the German occupation, demonstrating that economic deprivation, not family dislocation, sharply drove up juvenile crime rates. Wartime circumstances led authorities to view delinquent minors as victims, and provided the opportunity for reformers in psychiatry, social work, and law to fundamentally transform France’s punitive juvenile justice system into a profoundly therapeutic one. Vichy-era legislation thus formed the foundation of the modern juvenile justice system in France, which rarely incarcerates delinquent youth. In her examination of the critical but unexpected role the war and the authoritarian Vichy regime played in the transformation of France’s juvenile courts and institutions, Fishman has enriched our knowledge of daily life in France during World War II, refined our understanding of Vichy’s place in the historical development of France, and provided valuable insights into contemporary debates on juvenile justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJuvenile delinquencyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674272682?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674272682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674272682/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK